WEBVTT

00:01.570 --> 00:14.907
Ancient Faith Radio presents Homilies from All Saints, taken from the weekly sermons by Father Patrick Henry Reardon, priest at All Saints Orthodox Church in Chicago and senior editor of Touchstone Magazine.

00:15.367 --> 00:16.208
Here's Father Pat.

00:16.629 --> 00:22.316
The reading is from the Epistle to the Ephesians, beginning in chapter three.

00:25.740 --> 00:30.226
I bow my knees before the Father

00:32.162 --> 01:01.106
from whom all paternity in heaven and on earth is named, that according to the riches of His glory, He may grant you to be strengthened with might through His Spirit in the inner man, and that Christ may dwell in your hearts through faith, that you being rooted and grounded in love

01:03.202 --> 01:24.532
We have the power to comprehend with all the saints what is the breadth and length and height and depth and to know the love of Christ, which surpasses knowledge that you may be filled with all the fullness of God.

01:27.035 --> 01:31.922
Now to Him, who by the power at work within us

01:33.218 --> 01:37.223
He's able to do far more abundantly than all we ask or think.

01:38.906 --> 01:47.618
To Him be glory in the church and in Christ Jesus to all generations, forever and ever, amen.

01:48.619 --> 01:50.521
This is the word of the Lord.

01:56.169 --> 02:02.738
Except for the peace of our Lord and our Lady,

02:04.450 --> 02:12.980
My brothers and sisters in Christ, I do not normally preach on the feast day things.

02:13.000 --> 02:14.902
So maybe history is being made tonight.

02:17.545 --> 02:23.692
Beginning tonight, we start to celebrate the Feast of the Three Holy Hararks.

02:27.296 --> 02:33.042
Three bishops from the Church regards as especially to be credited

02:34.658 --> 02:39.465
with the preservation of the Christian faith in the fourth century.

02:42.349 --> 02:46.976
The Christian church in the fourth century endured many things, one of which was its freedom.

02:48.999 --> 02:53.064
With the Edich Milan in 313, they thought they had troubles up to that point.

02:53.465 --> 02:55.848
The real troubles were about to begin.

02:59.874 --> 03:02.578
Arias would have reduced the Christian faith

03:03.778 --> 03:14.013
to assert of Jesus' Unitarianism, that is, say, one God with a thin veneer of Jesus over it.

03:16.016 --> 03:21.524
And that is to say he would have created modern Christianity early.

03:26.391 --> 03:33.682
To repudiate that doctrine took the effort of most of a century.

03:35.842 --> 03:39.547
and lots of people put their shoulders to that wheel.

03:41.509 --> 03:46.596
But three fathers in particular are credited with its defeat.

03:48.278 --> 03:50.741
And those will be my three points tonight.

03:53.164 --> 04:00.073
Let's talk tonight about the depth, the height, and the breadth.

04:02.456 --> 04:04.018
Let's begin with the depth.

04:06.562 --> 04:16.814
Basil of Neo Caesarea in Cappadocia was born in the year 330 and died at the age of 49 in 379.

04:18.176 --> 04:30.711
If I've got my math right, I know I've got the dates right, I'm okay on dates, it's adding and subtracting I have trouble with.

04:30.731 --> 04:36.498
Why do we speak about basil and connection with the depth of the Christian faith?

04:38.658 --> 04:43.464
Basil did his liberal arts studies at Athens.

04:45.166 --> 04:54.558
And when he graduated from the academy, he immediately went to the desert and spent much of the rest of his youth as a monk.

04:56.100 --> 05:03.910
He wrote the rules that are the long and sharp rules that are the normal rules of Eastern monasticism.

05:04.931 --> 05:07.314
These are the rules that are recommended by name

05:07.938 --> 05:14.285
In the last chapter of the rule of Saint Benedict, which is the standard rule for Western monasticism.

05:15.486 --> 05:21.633
Benedict says in his last chapter of his rule, when you've done all these things, then check out the rule of Saint Basil.

05:28.020 --> 05:37.810
Basil eventually left the monastery in order to combat Aryanism.

05:39.362 --> 05:50.098
He perceived that arianism, the doctrine of arianism, was at odds with his own experience of Christ, of God as God's eternal son.

05:52.622 --> 06:05.722
He listened closely to the teaching of Arias and said himself, is this what I experience when as a monk I pray?

06:07.925 --> 06:08.626
And he answered,

06:09.218 --> 06:11.621
No, I'll be darned if it is."

06:13.083 --> 06:18.831
I'm not sure what the Greek for the darned is, but this is not what I experience.

06:20.414 --> 06:38.098
In other words, the depth of the Christian faith is not adequately addressed by Arianism, which is why Basil sided with the Archbishop of Alexandria, a man by the name of Athanasius,

06:39.330 --> 06:46.820
And he fought Arianism at a depth that Athanasius probably couldn't rival.

06:47.541 --> 06:54.050
He was far better educated and far better skilled in our argumentation.

06:55.752 --> 07:09.170
Basil represents the depth of the Christian faith, which is a matter of prayer, contemplation, and especially the ascetical life.

07:10.850 --> 07:18.320
And Babel saw without the ascetical life that we'd be no preservation of the Christian faith.

07:19.642 --> 07:23.207
That's why for basil, things like fast days are very important.

07:24.729 --> 07:27.993
I mean, in fact, that's pretty standard in the history of the church.

07:28.334 --> 07:31.918
You give up the two weekly fast days.

07:31.938 --> 07:32.679
You give up Lent.

07:33.240 --> 07:34.161
You give up these things.

07:34.702 --> 07:35.724
You're changing your mind.

07:36.284 --> 07:37.546
You're changing your mindset.

07:38.728 --> 07:40.530
You're altering the experience.

07:41.058 --> 07:42.099
of the Christian life.

07:42.940 --> 07:44.382
It won't be the Christian life anymore.

07:47.206 --> 07:54.295
Basil labored the rest of his life until 379, and then he died.

07:56.658 --> 07:58.360
Let's talk about the height.

08:00.062 --> 08:09.554
And that same year, 330, was born Gregory Nazianthus II, known in the

08:10.050 --> 08:12.432
East as Gregory of the Allusion.

08:13.914 --> 08:16.356
He was a boyhood friend of Basil.

08:17.437 --> 08:20.940
He went with Basil to Athens.

08:21.541 --> 08:25.725
He graduated from the Academy at Athens with Basil.

08:27.927 --> 08:34.373
Gregory and I as the answers were not nearly so interested in the active aesthetical life.

08:36.615 --> 08:39.858
He was certainly not interested in the politics of the church.

08:40.642 --> 08:50.276
In fact, when Bays will try to have him consecrated a bishop of a small town, Gregory packed his bags and headed out of town and hid out for a while.

08:50.497 --> 08:55.985
He treats this in the second of his theological orations.

08:59.270 --> 09:02.214
Gregory liked to think.

09:02.234 --> 09:02.955
He was a thinker.

09:04.497 --> 09:10.386
Now, there's a reason why he's one of three men in the history of the church.

09:11.586 --> 09:15.571
who are called Haul Teologos, the theologian.

09:16.292 --> 09:18.615
There are only three in the history of the church.

09:19.776 --> 09:23.060
We might try to get a fourth one here on Newport, but I don't think so.

09:23.461 --> 09:27.746
It's just three in the history of the church.

09:27.766 --> 09:36.717
St. John, the author of the Fourth Gospel, Gregory Nazianzis, and Simeon the New Theologian, if I knew it means a thousand years later.

09:38.279 --> 09:40.402
That's the most recent theologian we've had.

09:43.618 --> 09:45.761
Why did he get this name, the theologian?

09:47.863 --> 09:57.676
Fighting against arianism, he realized, would not be successful without a great refinement of thought.

09:59.037 --> 10:02.542
And Gregory the theologian was very much given to the study of philosophy.

10:03.723 --> 10:12.434
He is arguable that no one understood philosophy, the classical philosophy of Athens, at the depth and with the acuity

10:13.122 --> 10:14.724
of Gregory.

10:16.687 --> 10:17.868
But he was a retiring man.

10:19.891 --> 10:21.934
He didn't want to get involved in controversy.

10:23.896 --> 10:27.601
But then his friend Basil died in 379.

10:29.764 --> 10:36.273
And all of a sudden it is though the mantle of Basil had somehow fallen on the shoulders of Gregory.

10:37.695 --> 10:40.338
And after Basil's death he went to grip Basil's funeral.

10:41.506 --> 10:52.076
Someone there at the funeral persuaded him to come down to Constantinople and to be the pastor of the Nicene Party.

10:54.178 --> 11:00.284
That Nicene Party in Constantinople, which had fallen completely airy and otherwise.

11:01.366 --> 11:10.034
That Nicene Party was about the size of this parish, but they didn't have such a nice church to worship in as we have.

11:10.498 --> 11:12.860
The had, what we would call today, a storefront church.

11:15.142 --> 11:24.131
And Sunday by Sunday for two years, Gregory Naziances preached in that little church.

11:25.152 --> 11:26.733
He preached against Arianism.

11:28.815 --> 11:35.802
Gradually, little by little, the congregation began to grow in size.

11:38.004 --> 11:40.466
Gregory gave precise

11:41.026 --> 11:46.894
detailed refutations of all heresies against the Christian faith.

11:48.677 --> 11:50.539
When we ask the question, who is Jesus?

11:50.840 --> 11:53.223
The question.

11:53.243 --> 12:03.838
Gregory was able to answer that with his philosophical precision that put this area in Unitarianism to shame.

12:06.502 --> 12:09.266
He prepared for, in this way, he prepared for,

12:10.626 --> 12:36.050
The Council of 381, just two years later, the Council of 381, the Second Ecumenical Council, the Council of Constantinople, and he pastored that congregation for those two years, and that council elected a new archbishop for Constantinople, and he went back on home to Capidocia where he could study and read and pray.

12:38.178 --> 12:46.126
One of the other bishops at that council was Gregory of Nissa, by the way, the younger brother of Saint Basil.

12:48.068 --> 12:56.536
That's how the Christian faith was preserved in Cappadocia, Asia Minor, Greece, and Byzantium in the 4th century.

12:59.839 --> 13:02.862
Gregory himself lived on until the year 390.

13:04.784 --> 13:06.546
He lived exactly 60 years old.

13:10.914 --> 13:15.479
The third one will be what I call the breadth of the Christian faith.

13:18.143 --> 13:22.588
The breadth of the Christian faith because he was the popular preacher.

13:24.530 --> 13:36.004
He was the one who was able to take the Nicene theology, the theology of Basil, the theology of Gregory, and actually preach on it to ordinary people.

13:37.446 --> 13:38.147
He was born in 347.

13:38.667 --> 13:40.850
His name was John.

13:42.178 --> 13:43.339
He went as a boy.

13:43.399 --> 13:45.262
He went out into the Syrian desert.

13:46.283 --> 13:47.845
As a boy, he was a young man, his 20s.

13:48.786 --> 13:50.668
He had a very good education in Antioch.

13:51.349 --> 13:55.654
He went out to the Syrian desert where he quickly ruined his health with fasting.

13:56.996 --> 14:06.087
So this ex-monk came back into Antioch, and he became the parish priest at Antioch.

14:06.127 --> 14:08.370
People came from miles around here in preach.

14:09.250 --> 14:19.905
If they had had a radio station those days, he would have been the big podcast on the radio station.

14:19.925 --> 14:31.441
In the year 398, this parish priest at Antioch was made the Archbishop of Constantinople, a successor of Gregory Nazianzen.

14:33.063 --> 14:37.810
He held this position until his death in the year 407.

14:40.642 --> 14:52.513
During the last from 403 to 407, he was twice exiled and, in fact, died in exile.

14:52.813 --> 14:56.677
He surrounded himself with really quite competent people.

14:57.718 --> 15:10.610
His chief, Deacon, for example, was a man by the name of St. John Cashin, the author of the Institutes and the Conferences of Cashin, the founder of the large monastery, Marseille, in the south of Gaul.

15:10.690 --> 15:11.551
St. John Cashin.

15:12.512 --> 15:15.075
His Deaconess was a woman with the name of Olympia.

15:15.996 --> 15:25.867
There's a series of letters between Chrysostom and Olympia, which are still cited today, to bear witness to the vitality of the Church at that time.

15:28.129 --> 15:30.852
Chrysostom fell afoul of royalty.

15:32.034 --> 15:39.602
He was exiled in 403, was called back, was exiled again in 407.

15:40.002 --> 15:41.063
and died in exile.

15:43.806 --> 16:00.205
The Great Merit of Chrysostom is, I think, the fact that he brought the Nicene Antiochian Liturgy from Antioch over to Constantinople, where it replaced the Liturgy of St.

16:00.225 --> 16:00.566
Basil.

16:01.627 --> 16:04.170
Gregory has the answer to both the Liturgy of St.

16:04.190 --> 16:05.211
Basil in 379.

16:05.631 --> 16:07.954
It was replaced in 398.

16:08.674 --> 16:09.915
by John Chrysostom.

16:10.836 --> 16:18.625
John Chrysostom had a strong sense of what we would call the popularity of the Christian faith.

16:18.645 --> 16:20.427
He could preach to anybody and did.

16:21.468 --> 16:37.746
And in the series, means series of Greek Fathers, there's about 20 volumes, small print in columns, about 20 volumes of the sermons of Saint John Chrysostom.

16:38.050 --> 16:38.791
It was a great preacher.

16:40.573 --> 16:46.480
Of these three, the most important in the propagation of this faith was certainly John Chrysostom.

16:48.202 --> 17:07.826
When we, we orthodox come to worship every Sunday, and the prayers we say, the hemnography we use, comes to the liturgy of St. John Chrysostom, a man who has certainly done more to inform the Christian mind, the Christian heart throughout the centuries,

17:08.322 --> 17:12.269
of anybody after the New Testament itself.

17:12.289 --> 17:26.194
In these three men, in Basil, Gregory, and John Chrysostom, we perceive the depth, the height, and the breadth of the life in Christ.

17:29.410 --> 17:37.778
homilies from All Saints with father Pat Reardon, pastor of All Saints Orthodox Church in Chicago and senior editor of Touchstone magazine.

17:38.240 --> 17:41.330
